## See the Networks in Action

We just talked about giving form to the rich, layered networks in our minds. This is what that looks like.

We built a live example: an interactive guide for a fictional company, **Lǜ Sēnlín Technologies**, that makes modular kitchen gardens. This isn't a demo about gardening. It's a familiar scenario showing how you can turn a tangled web of options into clear, guided paths.

##### From Doubt to Direction

As you choose a frame size, add modules, and pick your crops, you're navigating a system built from reusable, interconnected parts. Watch how a single choice - like your location - instantly changes the options presented to you. No duplicated instructions. No inconsistency. Just a guide that adapts.

This is the end result: documentation that feels like a guided tour, not a manual. Always accurate, never contradictory, navigating the user to the right outcome - whether they're building a garden, troubleshooting a server, or managing a crisis.

The demo below is embedded directly into this guide. It's one small example of the complexity these systems can manage.

The demo below is embedded directly into this guide. It's one small example of the complexity these systems can manage - and the numbers behind it are staggering:

**This single guide has more possible paths than Wikipedia has pages.**

*Choose your location, power, climate, and crops. Behind each choice, the tree branches - but to you, it will feel like plain prose.*

Yet you build and maintain it with nothing more than a text editor. No database. No SaaS dashboard. Just Markdown and JSON in your repo.

